text: Good questions inside :+1:
yo <@U1HLABD1S> tell us about how it is to work on such an SDK compared to working on a normal app
it sounds pretty interesting

I guess It requires more upfront headwork than writing an app. In an app I can go forth an back with coding, refactoring, restructuring. If we would do that with our API, customers would kill us :smile:
Also, while app code can be tailored to the exact scenario, framework code needs to be generic while not overly complicated or bloated.
Other than that it's not all that different from coding an app. More documentation necessary :wink:
so basically anything you write is set in stone for a while and can’t be changed
you write the SDK docs or do you have someone who writes those?
It's not all that critical, we try to keep smaller breaking changes away from patch releases. Bigger breaking changes away from minor releases. Deprecate stuff if possible.
We have our public API completely documented (Javadoc) and have an extensive online guide (collection of articles, tips, tutorials) we write our own.
+ our Android documentation is available for Java _and_ Kotlin :slightly_smiling_face:
Here's a sample of our online guides: <https://pspdfkit.com/guides/android/current/features/text-search/>
Also we have a sample "catalog app" containing a lot of runnable examples

>Java _and_ Kotlin
:raised_hands:
Managed to push that forth :smile:
